  </section>

  <!-- ===== OUR APPROACH ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section" id="approach">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The SHARP Method</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">Why the SHARP Method produces Pre-IB Mathematics results other approaches can&rsquo;t</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">Developed by Jeremy Lim (LLB Hons, NUS Faculty of Law), the SHARP Method adapts legal analytical precision to mathematics &mdash; and it&rsquo;s the method behind A-Worthy&rsquo;s own annotated solution manuals, where every step carries a short &lsquo;Why:&rsquo; and common pitfalls are flagged with a &lsquo;Watch:&rsquo;.</p>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">See</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Most students lose marks before they write a single line of working &mdash; because they misread what the question is actually asking. In the See step, your child learns to decode every question the way a lawyer reads a contract: what is the command word (solve, simplify, factorise, differentiate, show that)? Is this a first-principles question or one to be done by the rules? Which topic &mdash; indices, surds, logarithms, trigonometry, calculus &mdash; is really being tested? For differentiation, this means recognising whether the limit definition is required or a standard rule applies. For surds, it means seeing the conjugate that will rationalise the denominator. By the time your child picks up the pen, they already know exactly which method to deploy.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Hit</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Once the question type is clear, your child reaches for the right tool &mdash; and states the rule before applying it. This isn&rsquo;t vague advice like &lsquo;show your working&rsquo;; it&rsquo;s a specific, named procedure for each topic: the limit definition for differentiation from first principles, the power rule for standard differentiation, the laws of logarithms for log equations, the conjugate method for surds, and the &lsquo;reverse the power rule, never drop the + C&rsquo; routine for integration. Writing the rule down first &mdash; exactly as our annotated manuals do &mdash; is what turns a guess into a method an examiner can award marks for.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Apply</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">This is where the method becomes actual working &mdash; line by line, nothing skipped. Your child constructs the solution under guided conditions with live tutor intervention, not by passively watching. For differentiation from first principles, that means substituting x + h everywhere, expanding, and cancelling the h in the denominator <em>before</em> letting h tend to zero &mdash; the move the whole method hinges on. For integration, it means carrying the + C every time. Jeremy provides real-time feedback on screen-shared workings, flagging missing steps and careless slips as they happen. With a maximum of 6 students, every child gets at least three individual feedback touches per session.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Refine &amp; Practise</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">The steps that turn good students into excellent ones. Your child self-checks every solution against a topic-specific checklist drawn straight from our &lsquo;Watch:&rsquo; callouts: did you let h tend to zero rather than substitute h = 0 too early? Did the + C survive? Do logs only ever take positive arguments? Then comes retrieval practice &mdash; the most underrated study technique in education. Your child reworks key problems from memory until the procedure is automatic. This is how technique transfers from the classroom to the exam hall: not through last-minute cramming, but through spaced, deliberate repetition &mdash; the kind our 120-question calculus drill set is built for.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== QUESTION-TYPE FRAMEWORKS ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section" id="frameworks">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Question-Type Frameworks</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">A named method for every question type in Pre-IB Mathematics</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">Most tuition centres teach &ldquo;how to do maths.&rdquo; We teach your child exactly which tool to reach for &mdash; and exactly how to use it &mdash; for every topic from indices to integration.</p>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Differentiation from First Principles</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">First principles is where most students panic &mdash; and where careless ones throw away easy marks. The method is fixed, so we drill it as a fixed routine. State the limit definition: f&prime;(x) = lim<sub>h&rarr;0</sub> [f(x + h) &minus; f(x)] / h. Substitute x + h for every x in the function. Expand and simplify the numerator. <strong>Cancel the h in the denominator</strong> &mdash; the single move the whole method hinges on &mdash; and only <em>then</em> let h tend to zero. The classic error is substituting h = 0 too early, which gives 0/0 and zero marks. Our annotated drill set walks through this on every question, so the discipline becomes second nature.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Differentiation by Rules</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Once first principles is understood, speed comes from the rules &mdash; applied cleanly, one term at a time. State the rule before using it: d/dx(x<sup>n</sup>) = n&middot;x<sup>n&minus;1</sup>. Differentiate term by term, bringing the power down and reducing it by one. Keep constants and coefficients explicit, and rewrite roots and reciprocals as powers first so the rule applies directly. We train your child to write the rule at the top of the working &mdash; examiners reward the stated method, and it eliminates the silent slips that cost marks under time pressure.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Tangents &amp; Stationary Points</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Gradient questions reward a clear procedure, not guesswork. For a tangent: find dy/dx, evaluate it at the given point for the gradient, then use y &minus; y&#8321; = m(x &minus; x&#8321;). For stationary points: set dy/dx = 0, solve for x, and substitute back for y. Then classify &mdash; second-derivative test or a sign check either side &mdash; to decide maximum, minimum, or point of inflexion. Each step is stated with its reason, so partial credit is never lost even if the final arithmetic slips.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Integration &amp; Areas</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Integration is differentiation in reverse, with two non-negotiable disciplines. Reverse the power rule: add one to the power and divide by the new power. For an indefinite integral, <strong>never drop the + C</strong> &mdash; the constant of integration, found from a known point. For a definite integral, substitute the upper limit, substitute the lower limit, and subtract &mdash; in that order. To find an area under a curve, integrate between the limits. These are exactly the two slips our &lsquo;Watch:&rsquo; callouts flag most often, so we drill them until they disappear.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Indices &amp; Surds</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Indices and surds underpin everything that follows, so we make the laws automatic. For indices: identify which law applies &mdash; product, quotient, power-of-a-power, negative, or fractional &mdash; and apply one law per line so each step is checkable. For surds: simplify by extracting square factors, and rationalise a denominator by multiplying top and bottom by the conjugate. The reasoning sits beside every line, so your child understands <em>why</em> each move is the natural one &mdash; not just that it works.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Logarithms &amp; Exponentials</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Logarithms intimidate students who treat them as a new kind of arithmetic rather than the inverse of exponentials. We anchor them to one idea: a logarithm is an exponent. Convert fluently between exponential and logarithmic form, then apply the laws &mdash; product, quotient, power, and change of base &mdash; one at a time. Solve equations by isolating the logarithm or the exponential first, and always check the domain, because a logarithm only ever takes a positive argument. Stated laws, line-by-line working, and a domain check turn logs from a feared topic into a reliable source of marks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== SHARP PLAYBOOK ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section playbook-section" id="playbook">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The SHARP Playbook</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">SHARP, mapped to every topic in Pre-IB Mathematics</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">Each row is a topic area. Each column is one SHARP step. Read across to see exactly what your child does at every stage &mdash; from decoding the question to retrieval practice.</p>

      <div class="playbook-matrix" role="table" aria-label="SHARP method mapped to each Pre-IB Mathematics topic">
        <div class="playbook-matrix__head" role="row">
          <div class="playbook-matrix__col-label" role="columnheader">Topic area</div>
          {sharpSteps.map((step) => (
            <div class="playbook-matrix__step" role="columnheader">
              <span class="playbook-letter" aria-hidden="true">{step.letter}</span>
              <span class="playbook-step-name">{step.name}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        {playbookRows.map((row, i) => (
          <div class="playbook-matrix__row" role="row">
            <div class="playbook-matrix__row-label" role="rowheader">
              <span class="playbook-paper">{row.paper}</span>
              <span class="playbook-section-name">{row.section}</span>
            </div>
            {row.steps.map((cell, j) => (
              <div class="playbook-matrix__cell" role="cell" data-step={sharpSteps[j].letter} data-step-name={sharpSteps[j].name}>
                <div class="playbook-matrix__cell-body">
                  <strong>{cell.title}</strong>
                  <span>{cell.note}</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="playbook-cta">
    <p>Ready to see the SHARP Method in action for your child?</p>
    <a href="/contact/" class="prog-cta__btn prog-cta__btn--primary">Book Free Assessment</a>
  </div>

  <!-- ===== BEFORE / AFTER ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section ba-section" id="before-after">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Before &amp; After</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">The same question, before and after the SHARP Method</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">What changes when a student follows the method instead of guessing. (Illustrative example &mdash; a typical first-principles question, not a real student script.)</p>

      <div class="ba-question">
        <span class="ba-q-label">Calculus &middot; Differentiation from first principles &middot; 3 marks</span>
        <p>Differentiate f(x) = x&sup2; from first principles.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ba-grid">
        <div class="ba-card ba-card--before">
          <span class="ba-tag ba-tag--before">Before</span>
          <p class="ba-answer">Writes &ldquo;f&prime;(x) = 2x&rdquo; with no working &mdash; or substitutes h = 0 straight away, reaching 0/0 and stopping.</p>
          <ul class="ba-notes">
            <li>Skips the limit definition entirely</li>
            <li>Substitutes h = 0 too early &rarr; 0/0, which is undefined</li>
            <li>No method shown, so the method marks are lost</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="ba-mark ba-mark--before">Typically 0&ndash;1 / 3</span>
        </div>

        <div class="ba-card ba-card--after">
          <span class="ba-tag ba-tag--after">After SHARP</span>
          <p class="ba-answer">States the definition; f(x + h) = (x + h)&sup2; = x&sup2; + 2xh + h&sup2;; so [f(x + h) &minus; f(x)] / h = (2xh + h&sup2;) / h = 2x + h; then lets h &rarr; 0 &rarr; <strong>f&prime;(x) = 2x</strong>.</p>
          <ul class="ba-notes">
            <li>States the limit definition first</li>
            <li><strong>Cancels the h</strong> before letting h &rarr; 0 &mdash; the move the method hinges on</li>
            <li>Every line shown &mdash; full method marks</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="ba-mark ba-mark--after">3 / 3</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="ba-footnote">Illustrative teaching example, not a real student script. Cancelling the h before taking the limit &mdash; rather than substituting h = 0 prematurely &mdash; is the discipline we drill at the <strong>Apply</strong> step of the SHARP Method.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== INSIDE A LESSON ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section lesson-flow" id="lesson-flow">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Inside a Lesson</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">What 90 minutes at A-Worthy actually looks like</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__intro">Most parents have never seen the inside of a maths tuition lesson. Here&rsquo;s exactly how a typical Year 3 or Year 4 Pre-IB Mathematics session unfolds &mdash; from the first warm-up question to the homework that gets set before students log off.</p>

      <ol class="lesson-timeline">
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">01</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">0 &ndash; 5 min &middot; Retrieval warm-up</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Five questions, ninety seconds each</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Five quick-fire questions on last week&rsquo;s techniques &mdash; a surd to rationalise, a law of logarithms, a derivative by the rules, a factorisation, an angle calculation. Students answer in the chat or on their whiteboards. Anyone who fumbles gets a one-line reminder before we move on. Retrieval is the most underrated study habit, so we build it into every session.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">02</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">5 &ndash; 15 min &middot; Question of the week</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Read the question before you solve</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">We project a real practice question on screen and walk through the <em>See</em> step together. What command word is being used? Is this a first-principles question or one for the rules? Which method will we reach for? By minute fifteen, every student knows exactly what method to use before they write a single line of working.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">03</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">15 &ndash; 30 min &middot; Method walkthrough</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">State the rule, then use the rule</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">First principles, the power rule, the laws of logarithms, the conjugate method for surds &mdash; whichever matches the day&rsquo;s focus. Jeremy demonstrates with a fully annotated model solution where every line carries its &lsquo;Why:&rsquo;, then deliberately writes a flawed version so students can spot the error. Naming the rule means students can reach for it again on exam day without the tutor in the room.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">04</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">30 &ndash; 60 min &middot; Live problem-solving &amp; feedback</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Three feedback touches per student</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Students attempt the question on screen-shared whiteboards or documents. Jeremy moves between solutions in real time, flagging issues as they happen &mdash; a dropped + C, an h substituted too early, a sign error in algebra, a missing domain check on a logarithm. This is where the small class size matters: every student gets at least three feedback touches in thirty minutes.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">05</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">60 &ndash; 75 min &middot; Peer checking</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Train the marker&rsquo;s eye</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Students swap solutions and check each other&rsquo;s working against the marking standard, line by line. Checking trains the marker&rsquo;s eye &mdash; the moment a student sees what loses marks in someone else&rsquo;s working, they stop making the same mistake in their own.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">06</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">75 &ndash; 90 min &middot; Exit ticket</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">No busywork goes home</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">A two-question exit ticket confirms what stuck. Jeremy sets one focused practice piece &mdash; usually fifteen minutes of work &mdash; with a fully annotated worked solution dropped on WhatsApp the next morning. No busywork. Every assignment maps to a specific weakness identified in that session.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="lesson-flow__note">Sessions run weekly via Zoom Pro with cloud recording, so any student who misses a week can catch up before the next one.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

